# AI Native Editor Agent Brief

This repository is the AI Native Editor prototype: a native C++ desktop game editor and runtime using CMake, GLFW, OpenGL, Dear ImGui docking, and the `ai_native_engine` library.

## Operating Rules

- Read the relevant docs and source before editing. Start with `README.md`, `docs/building.md`, `docs/architecture/system-architecture.md`, `docs/architecture/runtime-editor-separation.md`, `docs/ai/ai-editor-agent.md`, and `docs/ai/agent-backends-and-local-assist.md` when the task touches agent behavior.
- Keep changes narrow, additive, and aligned with the existing ownership boundaries.
- Do not store API keys, provider credentials, or private tokens in project files, generated agent memory, logs, or test fixtures.
- Do not copy Unity, Unreal, or other proprietary engine/editor internals or proprietary asset formats.
- Treat compile/build success, smoke-test success, runtime proof, and UI proof as separate claims. Report exactly what was verified.

## Architecture Boundaries

- `ai_native_engine` owns engine data and runtime behavior: entities, components, scene JSON serialization, validation, `EngineRuntime`, physics, and runtime systems.
- `ai_native_player` owns standalone project/scene loading and runtime ticking without editor UI.
- `EditorApp` owns editor UI, docked panels, project/session paths, selection, undo/redo, asset import records, script authoring files, plugin install state, chat/activity UI, and smoke hooks.
- `AgentOrchestrator` owns provider health, prompt wrapping, backend launch/execution, provider status, and Codex/OpenAI/Claude adapter behavior.
- `ToolGateway` owns schema-validated editor command batches. Scene and project mutations should flow through undoable editor commands, not uncontrolled provider writes.
- `ProviderResult` owns normalized provider output parsing for chat responses, proposed command batches, diagnostics, provider errors, and proposed file changes.

## Agent Workflow

- The visible user workflow should stay centered on one clear Agent surface.
- Short user requests should become editable implementation briefs with goal, inferred intent, project context, likely files, constraints, acceptance criteria, verification, and final-report expectations.
- When the user chooses Run With Codex or another development backend, run the generated/edited brief, not the raw short request.
- Send large Codex prompts through stdin (`codex exec -`) to avoid Windows command-line length failures.
- Local Prompt Assistant behavior is read-only. It may suggest text or intent chips, but it must not directly edit scenes, files, or assets.
- Local Tool Gateway may apply only explicit supported deterministic scene/project commands.
- Broad gameplay, editor-feature, or code-development requests must route to a development backend or produce a diagnostic. They must not silently create canned placeholder scene objects.
- External provider command batches and file changes must be shown as Proposed Actions and require approval before apply.
- Provider failures must fail closed with visible status such as connected, running, chat-only answer, proposed action waiting for approval, applied, applied with diagnostics, failed validation, timed out, backend unavailable, or not verified.
- Persist generated prompts, run starts, run completions, and summaries under `docs/agent-memory/run_log.jsonl` when agent-run artifacts are created.

## Verification

Use the smallest proof gate that covers the touched area, then state any remaining proof gap.

Common commands from the repository root:

```powershell
cmake --preset windows-ninja-debug
cmake --build --preset windows-ninja-debug
.\build\windows-ninja-debug\ai_native_editor.exe --smoke-test
.\scripts\run-smoke-tests.ps1
```

Focused smoke examples:

```powershell
.\build\windows-ninja-debug\ai_native_editor.exe --smoke-test --smoke-test-first-game
.\build\windows-ninja-debug\ai_native_editor.exe --smoke-test --smoke-test-runtime-logs --smoke-test-frames=120
.\build\windows-ninja-debug\ai_native_editor.exe --smoke-test --smoke-test-runtime-ui --project-root="build\runtime-ui-smoke" --smoke-test-frames=120
.\build\windows-ninja-debug\ai_native_editor.exe --smoke-test --smoke-test-provider-file-change --project-root="build\provider-file-change-smoke"
.\build\windows-ninja-debug\ai_native_editor.exe --smoke-test --smoke-test-project-builder --project-root="build\project-builder-smoke"
```

If the default debug executable is locked by a running editor, use a fresh build directory or `scripts/run-smoke-tests.ps1 -SkipBuild -BuildDir <path>` only when that directory is already built.

## Final Report

When finishing a task, report:

- Summary of behavior changed.
- Files changed and why.
- Verification commands run and pass/fail results.
- Remaining limitations or proof boundaries.
